<TITLE> Amnesty praises Brazil's Lula for torture comments </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 RIO DE JANEIRO, Feb 27 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Amnesty International praised Brazil's president on Wednesday for acknowledging torture in the country's prisons and expressed hope the government will put an end to the practice. President Luiz Inacio Lula da Silva said in a speech on Tuesday that "if beatings could straighten people out, criminals would leave jails as saints." Speaking in the crime-plagued city of Rio de Janeiro, where police often use brutal methods fighting drug gangs in the slums, Lula also said: "We will not fight crime with violence, we will fight crime with opportunities" like jobs for poor people. The human rights group said in a statement the president's words offered hope that the government will seek the eradication of torture, which it called a "dark stain." "Amnesty International greets with enthusiasm the acknowledgment by President Lula that the widespread practice of beatings and torture, which marks Brazil's prison system, is not a solution for serious public security problems." Brazil is known for its overcrowded prisons and detention centers where inmates are often kept in inhumane conditio
